## Notes on the implementation

- **Why it's truly sliding:** the count is recomputed on every request by evicting timestamps older than `now - windowMs`. There is no shared boundary at which all clients' counts drop to zero, so the classic fixed-window burst (up to `2 × maxRequests` straddling a reset) is impossible.
- **`X-RateLimit-Reset`:** set to when the *oldest in-window* timestamp expires — i.e. the next moment a slot frees — expressed in epoch seconds.
- **`Retry-After` / `retryAfter`:** seconds until the oldest timestamp falls out of the window, floored at 1 so clients never get told to retry in 0 seconds.
- **Eviction cost:** `splice(0, i)` is O(n) but timestamps are stored in chronological order and capped near `maxRequests`, so per-request work stays small.
- **Production note:** this store is in-memory and per-process. Across multiple workers/instances each process keeps its own counts, so the effective global limit is `maxRequests × instances`. For a shared limit, back the store with Redis (e.g. a sorted set per key using `ZREMRANGEBYSCORE` + `ZCARD` + `ZADD`), keeping the same algorithm.

